# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1945-washington-senators-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-washington-senators-season] The 1901 Washington Senators won 61 games, lost 72, and finished in sixth place in the American League in its first year as a major league team.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1901-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Jim Manning and played home games at the American League Park I.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1902-washington-senators-season] The **1902 Washington Senators** won 61 games, lost 75, and finished in sixth place in the American League.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1902-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Tom Loftus and played home games at the American League Park I.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] The **1903 Washington Senators** won 43 games, lost 94, and finished in eighth place in the American League.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Washington had finished in sixth place in each of the previous two seasons (the first two seasons of the American League's existence).
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] However, they fell to eighth and last in 1903.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Their only star player, Big Ed Delahanty, got drunk and fell off a bridge into Niagara Falls midway through the season.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] The Senators' pitching had always been bad, and indeed, they would allow the most runs in the AL, but without Delahanty the offense sputtered to a halt.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Their collective batting average was .231, bad even for the dead-ball era, and no one drove in more than 49 runs.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1904-washington-senators-season] The **1904 Washington Senators** won 38 games, lost 113, and finished in eighth place in the American League.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1904-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Malachi Kittridge and Patsy Donovan and played home games at National Park.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1904-washington-senators-season] Their winning percentage of .252 is fourth worst for any MLB team since 1900.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1905-washington-senators-season] The **1905 Washington Senators** won 64 games, lost 87, and finished in seventh place in the American League.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1905-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Jake Stahl and played home games at National Park.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1906-washington-senators-season] The **1906 Washington Senators** won 55 games, lost 95, and finished in seventh place in the American League.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1906-washington-senators-season] Shortstop Joe Cassidy died in March 1906 due to complications from typhoid and malaria.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1906-washington-senators-season] The Senators opened their 1906 season against the Philadelphia Athletics at Columbia Park in Philadelphia.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] The **1945 Washington Senators** won 87 games, lost 67, and finished in second place in the American League.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Ossie Bluege and played their home games at Griffith Stadium, where they drew 652,660 fans, fourth-most in the eight-team league.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] The 1945 Senators represented the 45th edition of the Major League Baseball franchise and were the last of the 20th-century Senators to place higher than fourth in the American League; the team moved to Minneapolis–Saint Paul in 1961 to become the modern Minnesota Twins.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] When the regular season ended on September 30, Washington trailed the pennant-winning Detroit Tigers (88–65) by 11⁄2 games.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] But because of World War II travel restrictions and the need to convert Griffith Stadium's playing field to host its autumn football tenants, the NFL Washington Redskins and Georgetown University, the Senators' 1945 schedule had actually ended seven days before, on Sunday, September 23.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] On that day, the "Griffs" stood one full game behind 86–64 Detroit.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] As the idle Senators waited, the Tigers had four games to play, two each against the fifth-place Cleveland Indians and third-place St.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] After splitting against the Indians, Detroit was rained out for three days in St.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] When the Tigers defeated the Browns 6–3 in the first game of the doubleheader on September 30 (on a come-from-behind, grand slam home run by Hank Greenberg), the Senators were mathematically eliminated and Detroit clinched the pennant.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] The second game of the twin bill was rained out.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] Outstanding pitching drove the 1945 Senators' success.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] Washington led the American League in team earned run average (2.92).
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] Its starting rotation featured four knuckleball artists—Roger Wolff, Dutch Leonard, Johnny Niggeling and Mickey Haefner—who combined for 60 victories.
[src:1945-washington-senators-season/1945-washington-senators-season] Wolff and Leonard posted sterling 2.12 and 2.13 earned run averages, third and fourth in the league.
